{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015fVtvU4XT6QGu8uYjGc2Zi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The CLI returned JSON with a `blocked: true` and `should_stop: true` indicating that the project root doesn't have a `.spec-anchor/config.toml` file. The error says \"ConfigError: .spec-anchor/config.toml not found under /tmp/spec-anchor-codex-e2e-f004-retest.iwMS9k\".\n\nBut wait - looking at the additional working directories, there's also:\n- /home/kazuki/public_html/llm-helper/docs/detailed-design\n- /home/kazuki/public_html/ec-spoke.local/docs/React+NestJS+Astro/drafts\n\n\n- The instructions are clear that I must treat the current working directory as the project root and not search parent directories or other paths, even if they have valid spec-anchor configs. The JSON response shows the operation is blocked and should stop, so I need to respect that boundary.\n\n- However, this is a ConfigError rather than a freshness/blocking issue—the config file simply doesn't exist in the primary working directory. The instructions specifically mention stopping when `freshness` is blocked or failed, but this error doesn't have a freshness field at all.\n\n- I should report this ConfigError to the user since the CLI can't proceed without a valid config at the current working directory. They may need to run the command from a different directory or initialize spec-anchor in this location first.\n\n- Actually, looking at the error response more carefully: `blocked: true`, `can_continue: false`, `should_stop: true` — these flags indicate I should stop regardless. The protocol says to relay the error JSON to the user and respect the stop signal.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":293,"cache_read_input_tokens":25575,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":293},"output_tokens